[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Given a curve, *E*, defined by some equation in a finite field (such as *E*: *y*2 = *x*3 + *ax* + *b*), point multiplication is defined as the repeated addition of a point along that curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Denote as *nP* = *P* + *P* + *P* + … + *P* for some scalar (integer) *n* and a point *P* = (*x*, *y*) that lies on the curve, *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This type of curve is known as a Weierstrass curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The security of modern ECC depends on the intractability of determining *n* from *Q* = *nP* given known values of *Q* and *P* if *n* is large (known as the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem by analogy to other cryptographic systems).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Reversing this process, i.e., given *Q=nP* and *P*, and determining *n*, can only be done by trying out all possible *n*—an effort that is computationally intractable if *n* is large.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] There are three commonly defined operations for elliptic curve points: addition, doubling and negation.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Point at infinity ⁠ ${\mathcal {O}}$ ⁠ is the identity element of elliptic curve arithmetic.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Adding it to any point results in that other point, including adding point at infinity to itself.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Point negation is finding such a point, that adding it to itself will result in point at infinity (⁠ ${\mathcal {O}}$ ⁠).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] With 2 distinct points, *P* and *Q*, addition is defined as the negation of the point resulting from the intersection of the curve, *E*, and the straight line defined by the points *P* and *Q*, giving the point, *R*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] These equations are correct when neither point is the point at infinity, ⁠ ${\mathcal {O}}$ ⁠, and if the points have different x coordinates (they're not mutual inverses).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This is important for the ECDSA verification algorithm where the hash value could be zero.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Where the points *P* and *Q* are coincident (at the same coordinates), addition is similar, except that there is no well-defined straight line through *P*, so the operation is closed using a limiting case, the tangent to the curve, *E*, at *P*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] where *a* is from the defining equation of the curve, *E*, above.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The straightforward way of computing a point multiplication is through repeated addition.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] However, there are more efficient approaches to computing the multiplication.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The simplest method is the double-and-add method, similar to square-and-multiply in modular exponentiation.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Note that both of the iterative methods above are vulnerable to timing analysis.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] See Montgomery Ladder below for an alternative approach.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] where *f* is the function for multiplying, *P* is the coordinate to multiply, *d* is the number of times to add the coordinate to itself.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Example: *100P* can be written as *2(2[P + 2(2[2(P + 2P)])])* and thus requires six point double operations and two point addition operations.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This algorithm requires log2(*d*) iterations of point doubling and addition to compute the full point multiplication.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] There are many variations of this algorithm such as using a window, sliding window, NAF, NAF-w, vector chains, and Montgomery ladder.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] In the windowed version of this algorithm, one selects a window size *w* and computes all $2^{w}$ values of $dP$ for $d=0,1,2,\dots ,2^{w}-1$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This algorithm has the same complexity as the double-and-add approach with the benefit of using fewer point additions (which in practice are slower than doubling).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Typically, the value of *w* is chosen to be fairly small making the pre-computation stage a trivial component of the algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] For the NIST recommended curves, $w=4$ is usually the best selection.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The entire complexity for a *n*-bit number is measured as $n+1$ point doubles and $2^{w}-2+{\tfrac {n}{w}}$ point additions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] In the sliding-window version, we look to trade off point additions for point doubles.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] We compute a similar table as in the windowed version except we only compute the points $dP$ for $d=2^{w-1},2^{w-1}+1,\dots ,2^{w}-1$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Effectively, we are only computing the values for which the most significant bit of the window is set.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This algorithm has the benefit that the pre-computation stage is roughly half as complex as the normal windowed method while also trading slower point additions for point doublings.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] In effect, there is little reason to use the windowed method over this approach, except that the former can be implemented in constant time.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The algorithm requires $w-1+n$ point doubles and at most $2^{w-1}-1+{\tfrac {n}{w}}$ point additions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] In the non-adjacent form we aim to make use of the fact that point subtraction is just as easy as point addition to perform fewer (of either) as compared to a sliding-window method.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This produces the NAF needed to now perform the multiplication.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This algorithm requires the pre-computation of the points $\lbrace 1,3,5,\dots ,2^{w-1}-1\rbrace P$ and their negatives, where P is the point to be multiplied.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] On typical Weierstrass curves, if $P=\lbrace x,y\rbrace$ then $-P=\lbrace x,-y\rbrace$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] So in essence the negatives are cheap to compute.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The wNAF guarantees that on average there will be a density of ${\tfrac {1}{w+1}}$ point additions (slightly better than the unsigned window).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] It requires 1 point doubling and $2^{w-2}-1$ point additions for precomputation.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The algorithm then requires n point doublings and ${\tfrac {n}{w+1}}$ point additions for the rest of the multiplication.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] One property of the NAF is that we are guaranteed that every non-zero element $d_{i}$ is followed by at least $w-1$ additional zeroes.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This is because the algorithm clears out the lower w bits of d with every subtraction of the output of the *mods* function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This observation can be used for several purposes.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] After every non-zero element the additional zeroes can be implied and do not need to be stored.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Secondly, the multiple serial divisions by 2 can be replaced by a division by $2^{w}$ after every non-zero $d_{i}$ element and divide by 2 after every zero.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] It has been shown that through application of a FLUSH+RELOAD side-channel attack on OpenSSL, the full private key can be revealed after performing cache-timing against as few as 200 signatures performed.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The Montgomery ladder approach computes the point multiplication in a *fixed* number of operations.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This can be beneficial when timing, power consumption, or branch measurements are exposed to an attacker performing a side-channel attack.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The algorithm uses the same representation as from double-and-add.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This algorithm has in effect the same speed as the double-and-add approach except that it computes the same number of point additions and doubles regardless of the value of the multiplicand *d*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This means that at this level the algorithm does not leak any information through branches or power consumption.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] However, it has been shown that through application of a FLUSH+RELOAD side-channel attack on OpenSSL, the full private key can be revealed after performing cache-timing against only one signature at a very low cost.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Using Lucas chains provides an optimized sequence of doubling and adds compared to the Montgomery ladder, which is faster on larger multiples (longer chains).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] PRAC is also published by Montgomery, with the "reference implementation" being GMP-ECM.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] DJ Bernstein mentions a number of such schemes in 2017.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The security of a cryptographic implementation is likely to face the threat of the so-called timing attacks which exploits the data-dependent timing characteristics of the implementation.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Machines running cryptographic implementations consume variable amounts of time to process different inputs and so the timings vary based on the encryption key.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] To resolve this issue, cryptographic algorithms are implemented in a way which removes data dependent variable timing characteristic from the implementation leading to the so-called constant-time implementations.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The Montgomery ladder is an x -coordinate only algorithm for elliptic curve point multiplication and is based on the double and add rules over a specific set of curves known as Montgomery curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The algorithm has a conditional branching such that the condition depends on a secret bit.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] So a straightforward implementation of the ladder won't be constant time and has the potential to leak the secret bit.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] This problem has been addressed in literature and several constant time implementations are known.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The constant time Montgomery ladder algorithm is as given below which uses two functions CSwap and Ladder-Step.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] In the return value of the algorithm Z2p-2 is the value of Z2−1 computed using the Fermat's little theorem.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The Ladder-Step function (given below) used within the ladder is the core of the algorithm and is a combined form of the differential add and doubling operations.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The field constant a24 is defined as a24 = $(A+2)/4$ , where A is a parameter of the underlying Montgomery curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The CSwap function manages the conditional branching and helps the ladder to run following the requirements of a constant time implementation.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The function swaps the pair of field elements $\langle$ X2,Z2 $\rangle$ and $\langle$ X3,Z3 $\rangle$ only if b = 1 and this is done without leaking any information about the secret bit.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Various methods of implementing CSwap have been proposed in literature.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] A lesser costly option to manage the constant time requirement of the Montgomery ladder is conditional select which is formalised through a function CSelect.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The work provided a couple of 64-bit assembly implementations targeting the AMD64 architecture.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The implementations were developed using a tool known as *qhasm* which can generate high-speed assembly language cryptographic programs.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The function CSwap was used in the implementations of these ladders.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] After that there has been several attempts to optimise the ladder implementation through hand-written assembly programs out of which the notion of CSelect was first used in and then in.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Apart from using sequential instructions, vector instructions have also been used to optimise the ladder computation through various works.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Along with AMD64, attempts have also been made to achieve efficient implementations on other architectures like ARM.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The works and provides efficient implementations targeting the ARM architecture.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] The libraries lib25519 and are two state-of-art libraries containing efficient implementations of the Montgomery ladder for Curve25519.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Nevertheless, the libraries have implementations of other cryptographic primitives as well.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Apart from Curve25519, there have been several attempts to compute the ladder over other curves at various security levels.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] Efficient implementations of the ladder over the standard curve Curve448 at 224-bit security level have also been studied in literature.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] A curve named Curve41417 providing security just over 200 bits was proposed in which a variant of Karatsuba strategy was used to implement the field multiplication needed for the related ECC software.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] In pursuit of searching Montgomery curves that are competitive to Curve25519 and Curve448 research has been done and couple of curves were proposed along with efficient sequential and vectorised implementations of the corresponding ladders.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve-point-multiplication] At 256-bit security level efficient implementations of the ladder have also been addressed through three different Montgomery curves.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In mathematics, an **elliptic curve** is a smooth, projective, algebraic curve of genus one, on which there is a specified point O.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] An elliptic curve is defined over a field K and describes points in *K*2, the Cartesian product of K with itself.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The curve is required to be non-singular, which means that the curve has no cusps or self-intersections.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] (This is equivalent to the condition 4*a*3 + 27*b*2 ≠ 0, that is, being square-free in x.) It is usually understood that the curve is embedded in the projective plane, with the point O being the unique point at infinity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Many sources define an elliptic curve to be simply a curve given by an equation of this form.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] An elliptic curve is an abelian variety – that is, it has a group law defined algebraically, with respect to which it is an abelian group – and O serves as the identity element.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If *y*2 = *P*(*x*), where P is any polynomial of degree three in x with no repeated roots, the solution set is a nonsingular plane curve of genus one, an elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If P has degree four and is square-free this equation again describes a plane curve of genus one; however, it has no natural choice of identity element.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] More generally, any algebraic curve of genus one, for example the intersection of two quadric surfaces embedded in three-dimensional projective space, is called an elliptic curve, provided that it is equipped with a marked point to act as the identity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Using the theory of elliptic functions, it can be shown that elliptic curves defined over the complex numbers correspond to embeddings of the torus into the complex projective plane.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The torus is also an abelian group, and this correspondence is also a group isomorphism.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves are especially important in number theory, and constitute a major area of current research; for example, they were used in Andrew Wiles's proof of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] They also find applications in elliptic curve cryptography (ECC) and integer factorization.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] An elliptic curve is *not* an ellipse in the sense of a projective conic, which has genus zero: see elliptic integral for the origin of the term.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] However, there is a natural representation of real elliptic curves with shape invariant *j* ≥ 1 as ellipses in the hyperbolic plane $\mathbb {H} ^{2}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Specifically, the intersections of the Minkowski hyperboloid with quadric surfaces characterized by a certain constant-angle property produce the Steiner ellipses in $\mathbb {H} ^{2}$ (generated by orientation-preserving collineations).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Here, the vertex of the hyperboloid serves as the identity on each trajectory curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Topologically, a complex elliptic curve is a torus, while a complex ellipse is a sphere.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Although the formal definition of an elliptic curve requires some background in algebraic geometry, it is possible to describe some features of elliptic curves over the real numbers using only introductory algebra and geometry.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] after a linear change of variables (a and b are real numbers).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This type of equation is called a *Weierstrass normal form*, *Weierstrass form*, or *Weierstrass equation*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The definition of elliptic curve also requires that the curve be non-singular.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Geometrically, this means that the graph has no cusps, self-intersections, or isolated points.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] (see J-invariant#Algebraic_definition for the derivation).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Although the factor −16 is irrelevant to whether or not the curve is non-singular, this definition of the discriminant is useful in a more advanced study of elliptic curves.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The real graph of a non-singular curve has *two* components if its discriminant is positive, and *one* component if it is negative.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] For example, in the graphs shown in figure to the right, the discriminant in the first case is 64, and in the second case is −368.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This resulting equation is defined on the whole projective plane, and the curve it defines projects onto the elliptic curve of interest.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] To find its intersection with the line at infinity, we can just posit $Z=0$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This implies $X^{3}=0$ , which in a field means $X=0$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Y on the other hand can take any value, and thus all triplets $(0,Y,0)$ satisfy the equation.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In projective geometry this set is simply the point $O=[0:1:0]$ , which is thus the unique intersection of the curve with the line at infinity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Since the curve is symmetric about the x axis, given any point P, we can take −*P* to be the point opposite it.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] We then have $-O=O$ , as O lies on the XZ plane, so that $-O$ is also the symmetrical of O about the origin, and thus represents the same projective point.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If P and Q are two points on the curve, then we can uniquely describe a third point *P* + *Q* in the following way.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] First, draw the line that intersects P and Q.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This will generally intersect the cubic at a third point, R.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] We then take *P* + *Q* to be −*R*, the point opposite R.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This definition for addition works except in a few special cases related to the point at infinity and intersection multiplicity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The first is when one of the points is O.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Here, we define *P* + *O* = *P* = *O* + *P*, making O the identity of the group.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If *P* = *Q*, we only have one point, thus we cannot define the line between them.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In this case, we use the tangent line to the curve at this point as our line.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In most cases, the tangent will intersect a second point R, and we can take its opposite.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If P and Q are opposites of each other, we define *P* + *Q* = *O*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Lastly, if P is an inflection point (a point where the concavity of the curve changes), we take R to be P itself, and *P* + *P* is simply the point opposite itself, i.e. itself.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Let K be a field over which the curve is defined (that is, the coefficients of the defining equation or equations of the curve are in K) and denote the curve by E.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Then the K-rational points of E are the points on E whose coordinates all lie in K, including the point at infinity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The set of K-rational points is denoted by *E*(*K*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] *E*(*K*) is a group, because properties of polynomial equations show that if P is in *E*(*K*), then −*P* is also in *E*(*K*), and if two of P, Q, R are in *E*(*K*), then so is the third.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Additionally, if K is a subfield of L, then *E*(*K*) is a subgroup of *E*(*L*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The above groups can be described algebraically as well as geometrically.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Given the curve *y*2 = *x*3 + *bx* + *c* over the field K (whose characteristic we assume to be neither 2 nor 3), and points *P* = (*xP*, *yP*) and *Q* = (*xQ*, *yQ*) on the curve, assume first that *xP* ≠ *xQ* (case *1*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The line equation and the curve equation intersect at the points xP, xQ, and xR, so the equations have identical y values at these values.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] and because both equations are cubics, they must be the same polynomial up to a scalar.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] and this is an element of K, because s is.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If *xP* = *xQ*, then there are two options: if *yP* = −*yQ* (case *3*), including the case where *yP* = *yQ* = 0 (case *4*), then the sum is defined as 0; thus, the inverse of each point on the curve is found by reflecting it across the x axis.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The slope is given by the tangent to the curve at (*x**P*, *y**P*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] For a general cubic curve not in Weierstrass normal form, we can still define a group structure by designating one of its nine inflection points as the identity O.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In the projective plane, each line will intersect a cubic at three points when accounting for multiplicity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] For a point P, −*P* is defined as the unique third point on the line passing through O and P.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Then, for any P and Q, *P* + *Q* is defined as −*R* where R is the unique third point on the line containing P and Q.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] For an example of the group law over a non-Weierstrass curve, see Hessian curves.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] A curve *E* defined over the field of rational numbers is also defined over the field of real numbers.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Therefore, the law of addition (of points with real coordinates) by the tangent and secant method can be applied to *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The explicit formulae show that the sum of two points *P* and *Q* with rational coordinates has again rational coordinates, since the line joining *P* and *Q* has rational coefficients.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This way, one shows that the set of rational points of *E* forms a subgroup of the group of real points of *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This section is concerned with points *P* = (*x*, *y*) of *E* such that *x* is an integer.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Rational points can be constructed by the method of tangents and secants detailed above, starting with a *finite* number of rational points.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] More precisely the Mordell–Weil theorem states that the group *E*(**Q**) is a finitely generated (abelian) group.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] By the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups it is therefore a finite direct sum of copies of **Z** and finite cyclic groups.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The proof of the theorem involves two parts.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The first part shows that for any integer *m* > 1, the quotient group *E*(**Q**)/*mE*(**Q**) is finite (this is the weak Mordell–Weil theorem).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Second, introducing a height function *h* on the rational points *E*(**Q**) defined by *h*(*P*0) = 0 and *h*(*P*) = log max(|*p*|, |*q*|) if *P* (unequal to the point at infinity *P*0) has as abscissa the rational number *x* = *p*/*q* (with coprime *p* and *q*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This height function *h* has the property that *h*(*mP*) grows roughly like the square of *m*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Moreover, only finitely many rational points with height smaller than any constant exist on *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The theorem however doesn't provide a method to determine any representatives of *E*(**Q**)/*mE*(**Q**).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The rank of *E*(**Q**) is the number of copies of **Z** in *E*(**Q**) or, equivalently, the number of independent points of infinite order.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture is concerned with determining the rank.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] One conjectures that it can be arbitrarily large, even if only examples with relatively small rank are known.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] It has rank 20, found by Noam Elkies and Zev Klagsbrun in 2020.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Curves of rank higher than 20 have been known since 1994, with lower bounds on their ranks ranging from 21 to 29, but their exact ranks are not known and in particular it is not proven which of them have higher rank than the others or which is the true "current champion".
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Moreover, elliptic curves whose Mordell–Weil groups over **Q** have the same torsion groups belong to a parametrized family.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture (BSD) is one of the Millennium problems of the Clay Mathematics Institute.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The conjecture relies on analytic and arithmetic objects defined by the elliptic curve in question.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] At the analytic side, an important ingredient is a function of a complex variable, *L*, the Hasse–Weil zeta function of *E* over **Q**.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This function is a variant of the Riemann zeta function and Dirichlet L-functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] It is defined as an Euler product, with one factor for every prime number *p*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The zeta function of an elliptic curve over a finite field **F***p* is, in some sense, a generating function assembling the information of the number of points of *E* with values in the finite field extensions **F***pn* of **F***p*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] where the 'trace of Frobenius' term $a_{p}$ is defined to be the difference between the 'expected' number $p+1$ and the number of points on the elliptic curve E over $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ , viz.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] We may define the same quantities and functions over an arbitrary finite field of characteristic p , with $q=p^{n}$ replacing p everywhere.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The L-function of *E* over **Q** is then defined by collecting this information together, for all primes *p*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] where *N* is the conductor of *E*, i.e. the product of primes with bad reduction $(\Delta (E\mod p)=0$ ), in which case *ap* is defined differently from the method above: see Silverman (1986) below.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This product converges for Re(*s*) > 3/2 only.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Hasse's conjecture affirms that the *L*-function admits an analytic continuation to the whole complex plane and satisfies a functional equation relating, for any *s*, *L*(*E*, *s*) to *L*(*E*, 2 − *s*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In 1999 this was shown to be a consequence of the proof of the Shimura–Taniyama–Weil conjecture, which asserts that every elliptic curve over *Q* is a modular curve, which implies that its *L*-function is the *L*-function of a modular form whose analytic continuation is known.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] One can therefore speak about the values of *L*(*E*, *s*) at any complex number *s*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The *Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture* relates the arithmetic of the curve to the behaviour of this *L*-function at *s* = 1.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] It affirms that the vanishing order of the *L*-function at *s* = 1 equals the rank of *E* and predicts the leading term of the Laurent series of *L*(*E*, *s*) at that point in terms of several quantities attached to the elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Let *K* = **F***q* be the finite field with *q* elements and *E* an elliptic curve defined over *K*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In other words, the number of points on the curve grows proportionally to the number of elements in the field.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This fact can be understood and proven with the help of some general theory; see local zeta function and étale cohomology for example.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The set of points *E*(**F***q*) is a finite abelian group.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] It is always cyclic or the product of two cyclic groups.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] over **F**71 has 72 points (71 affine points including (0,0) and one point at infinity) over this field, whose group structure is given by **Z**/2**Z** × **Z**/36**Z**.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The number of points on a specific curve can be computed with Schoof's algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] where the field *Kn* is the (unique up to isomorphism) extension of *K* = **F***q* of degree *n* (that is, $K_{n}=F_{q^{n}}$ ).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The zeta function is a rational function in *T*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The Sato–Tate conjecture is a statement about how the error term $2{\sqrt {q}}$ in Hasse's theorem varies with the different primes *q*, if an elliptic curve E over **Q** is reduced modulo q.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] It was proven (for almost all such curves) in 2006 due to the results of Taylor, Harris and Shepherd-Barron, and says that the error terms are equidistributed.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves over finite fields are notably applied in cryptography and for the factorization of large integers.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] These algorithms often make use of the group structure on the points of *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Algorithms that are applicable to general groups, for example the group of invertible elements in finite fields, **F****q*, can thus be applied to the group of points on an elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] For example, the discrete logarithm is such an algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The interest in this is that choosing an elliptic curve allows for more flexibility than choosing *q* (and thus the group of units in **F***q*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Also, the group structure of elliptic curves is generally more complicated.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves can be defined over any field *K*; the formal definition of an elliptic curve is a non-singular projective algebraic curve over *K* with genus 1 and endowed with a distinguished point defined over *K*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Here *p* and *q* are elements of *K* such that the right hand side polynomial *x*3 − *px* − *q* does not have any double roots.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] for arbitrary constants *b*2, *b*4, *b*6 such that the polynomial on the right-hand side has distinct roots (the notation is chosen for historical reasons).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] provided that the variety it defines is non-singular.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If characteristic were not an obstruction, each equation would reduce to the previous ones by a suitable linear change of variables.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] One typically takes the curve to be the set of all points (*x*,*y*) which satisfy the above equation and such that both *x* and *y* are elements of the algebraic closure of *K*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Points of the curve whose coordinates both belong to *K* are called ***K*-rational points**.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Many of the preceding results remain valid when the field of definition of *E* is a number field *K*, that is to say, a finite field extension of **Q**.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] In particular, the group *E(K)* of *K*-rational points of an elliptic curve *E* defined over *K* is finitely generated, which generalizes the Mordell–Weil theorem above.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] A theorem due to Loïc Merel shows that for a given integer *d*, there are (up to isomorphism) only finitely many groups that can occur as the torsion groups of *E*(*K*) for an elliptic curve defined over a number field *K* of degree *d*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] More precisely, there is a number *B*(*d*) such that for any elliptic curve *E* defined over a number field *K* of degree *d*, any torsion point of *E*(*K*) is of order less than *B*(*d*).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] As for the integral points, Siegel's theorem generalizes to the following: Let *E* be an elliptic curve defined over a number field *K*, *x* and *y* the Weierstrass coordinates.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Then there are only finitely many points of *E(K)* whose *x*-coordinate is in the ring of integers *O**K*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The properties of the Hasse–Weil zeta function and the Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture can also be extended to this more general situation.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The formulation of elliptic curves as the embedding of a torus in the complex projective plane follows naturally from a curious property of Weierstrass's elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Here, *g*2 and *g*3 are constants; ℘(*z*) is the Weierstrass elliptic function and ℘′(*z*) its derivative.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] It should be clear that this relation is in the form of an elliptic curve (over the complex numbers).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The Weierstrass functions are doubly periodic; that is, they are periodic with respect to a lattice Λ; in essence, the Weierstrass functions are naturally defined on a torus *T* = **C**/Λ.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] This map is a group isomorphism of the torus (considered with its natural group structure) with the chord-and-tangent group law on the cubic curve which is the image of this map.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] It is also an isomorphism of Riemann surfaces from the torus to the cubic curve, so topologically, an elliptic curve is a torus.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] If the lattice Λ is related by multiplication by a non-zero complex number c to a lattice *c*Λ, then the corresponding curves are isomorphic.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Isomorphism classes of elliptic curves are specified by the j-invariant.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The isomorphism classes can be understood in a simpler way as well.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] The constants *g*2 and *g*3, called the modular invariants, are uniquely determined by the lattice, that is, by the structure of the torus.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] However, all real polynomials factorize completely into linear factors over the complex numbers, since the field of complex numbers is the algebraic closure of the reals.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] with j-invariant *j*(*τ*) and *λ*(*τ*) is sometimes called the modular lambda function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] For example, let *τ* = 2*i*, then *λ*(2*i*) = (−1 + √2)4 which implies *g*′2, *g*′3, and therefore *g*′23 − 27*g*′32 of the formula above are all algebraic numbers if τ involves an imaginary quadratic field.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Note that the uniformization theorem implies that every compact Riemann surface of genus one can be represented as a torus.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] for integers a and b in the range 0 ≤ (*a*, *b*) < *n*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] M(*w*, *z*) is the arithmetic–geometric mean of w and z.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] At each step of the arithmetic–geometric mean iteration, the signs of zn arising from the ambiguity of geometric mean iterations are chosen such that |*wn* − *zn*| ≤ |*wn* + *zn*| where wn and zn denote the individual arithmetic mean and geometric mean iterations of w and z, respectively.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Over the complex numbers, every elliptic curve has nine inflection points.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Every line through two of these points also passes through a third inflection point; the nine points and 12 lines formed in this way form a realization of the Hesse configuration.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] where $\operatorname {Div} ^{0}$ is the group of divisors of degree 0.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves over finite fields are used in some cryptographic applications as well as for integer factorization.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-curve] Typically, the general idea in these applications is that a known algorithm which makes use of certain finite groups is rewritten to use the groups of rational points of elliptic curves.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] In integral calculus, an **elliptic integral** is one of a number of related functions defined as the value of certain integrals, which were first studied by Giulio Fagnano and Leonhard Euler (c.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Their name originates from their connection with the problem of finding the arc length of an ellipse.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] where *R* is a rational function of its two arguments, *P* is a polynomial of degree 3 or 4 with no repeated roots, and *c* is a constant.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] In general, integrals in this form cannot be expressed in terms of elementary functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Exceptions to this general rule are when *P* has repeated roots, when *R*(*x*, *y*) contains no odd powers of *y*, and when the integral is pseudo-elliptic.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] However, with the appropriate reduction formula, every elliptic integral can be brought into a form that involves integrals over rational functions and the three Legendre canonical forms, also known as the elliptic integrals of the first, second and third kind.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Besides the Legendre form given below, the elliptic integrals may also be expressed in Carlson symmetric form.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Additional insight into the theory of the elliptic integral may be gained through the study of the Schwarz–Christoffel mapping.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Historically, elliptic functions were discovered as inverse functions of elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Each of the above three quantities is completely determined by any of the others (given that they are non-negative).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The other argument can likewise be expressed as *φ*, the *amplitude*, or as *x* or *u*, where *x* = sin *φ* = sn *u* and sn is one of the Jacobian elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Specifying the value of any one of these quantities determines the others.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The latter is sometimes called the *delta amplitude* and written as Δ(*φ*) = dn *u*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Sometimes the literature also refers to the *complementary parameter*, the *complementary modulus,* or the *complementary modular angle*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] These are further defined in the article on quarter periods.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] In this notation, the use of a vertical bar as delimiter indicates that the argument following it is the "parameter" (as defined above), while the backslash indicates that it is the modular angle.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] There are still other conventions for the notation of elliptic integrals employed in the literature.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The notation with interchanged arguments, *F*(*k*, *φ*), is often encountered; and similarly *E*(*k*, *φ*) for the integral of the second kind.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Abramowitz and Stegun substitute the integral of the first kind, *F*(*φ*, *k*), for the argument φ in their definition of the integrals of the second and third kinds, unless this argument is followed by a vertical bar: i.e.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Moreover, their complete integrals employ the *parameter* *k*2 as argument in place of the modulus *k*, i.e.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] And the integral of the third kind defined by Gradshteyn and Ryzhik, Π(*φ*, *n*, *k*), puts the amplitude φ first and not the "characteristic" n.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Thus one must be careful with the notation when using these functions, because various reputable references and software packages use different conventions in the definitions of the elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] For example, Wolfram's Mathematica software and Wolfram Alpha define the complete elliptic integral of the first kind in terms of the parameter *m*, instead of the elliptic modulus *k*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] With *x* = sn(*u*, *k*) one has: $F(x;k)=u;$ demonstrating that this Jacobian elliptic function is a simple inverse of the incomplete elliptic integral of the first kind.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The meridian arc length from the equator to latitude *φ* is written in terms of *E*: $m(\varphi )=a\left(E(\varphi ,e)+{\frac {d^{2}}{d\varphi ^{2}}}E(\varphi ,e)\right),$ where *a* is the semi-major axis, and *e* is the eccentricity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The number *n* is called the **characteristic** and can take on any value, independently of the other arguments.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Note though that the value Π(1; ⁠π/2⁠ | *m*) is infinite, for any *m*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Elliptic Integrals are said to be 'complete' when the amplitude *φ* = ⁠π/2⁠ and therefore *x* = 1.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] where *n*!! denotes the double factorial.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The complete elliptic integral of the first kind is sometimes called the quarter period.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] If *k*2 = *λ*(*i*√*r*) and $r\in \mathbb {Q} ^{+}$ (where λ is the modular lambda function), then *K*(*k*) is expressible in closed form in terms of the gamma function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] More generally, the condition that ${\frac {iK'}{K}}={\frac {iK\left({\sqrt {1-k^{2}}}\right)}{K(k)}}$ be in an imaginary quadratic field is sufficient.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Keeping only the first two terms is correct to 0.01 precision for *k* < ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] A second solution to this equation is $K\left({\sqrt {1-k^{2}}}\right)$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Here, we use the complete elliptic integral of the first kind with the *parameter* m instead, because the squaring function introduces problems when inverting in the complex plane.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The equation $\tau =i{\frac {K[1-m]}{K[m]}}$ can then be solved (provided that a solution m exists) by $m={\frac {\theta _{2}(\tau )^{4}}{\theta _{3}(\tau )^{4}}}$ which is in fact the modular lambda function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] For an ellipse with semi-major axis *a* and semi-minor axis *b* and eccentricity *e* = √1 − *b*2/*a*2, the complete elliptic integral of the second kind *E*(*e*) is equal to one quarter of the circumference *C* of the ellipse measured in units of the semi-major axis *a*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Like the integral of the first kind, the complete elliptic integral of the second kind can be computed very efficiently using the arithmetic–geometric mean.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] In practice, the arithmetic-geometric mean would simply be computed up to some limit.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] This formula converges quadratically for all |*k*| ≤ 1.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] To speed up computation further, the relation *c**n* + 1 = ⁠*cn*2/4*a**n* + 1⁠ can be used.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Just like the complete elliptic integrals of the first and second kind, the complete elliptic integral of the third kind can be computed very efficiently using the arithmetic-geometric mean.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] In 1829, Jacobi defined the **Jacobi zeta function**: $Z(\varphi ,k)=E(\varphi ,k)-{\frac {E(k)}{K(k)}}F(\varphi ,k).$ It is periodic in $\varphi$ with minimal period $\pi$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] It is related to the Jacobi zn function by $Z(\varphi ,k)=\operatorname {zn} (F(\varphi ,k),k)$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Whittaker and Watson (1927)), sometimes Z means Wikipedia's $\operatorname {zn}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] King (1924)) use Z for both Wikipedia's Z and $\operatorname {zn}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] The Legendre's relation for tangential modular counterparts results directly from the Legendre's identity for Pythagorean modular counterparts by using the Landen modular transformation on the Pythagorean counter modulus.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] For the lemniscatic case, the elliptic modulus or specific eccentricity ε is equal to half the square root of two.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Now the modular general case is worked out.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] For this purpose, the derivatives of the complete elliptic integrals are derived after the modulus $\varepsilon$ and then they are combined.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] And then the Legendre's identity balance is determined.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Legendre's identity includes products of any two complete elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] In relation to the $\varepsilon$ the equation balance constantly gives the value zero.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] Because if the derivative of a continuous function constantly takes the value zero, then the concerned function is a constant function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/elliptic-integral] This means that this function results in the same function value for each abscissa value $\varepsilon$ and the associated function graph is therefore a horizontal straight line.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] In mathematics, the **Mordell–Weil theorem** states that for an abelian variety A over a number field K , the group $A(K)$ of *K*-rational points of A is a finitely-generated abelian group, called the Mordell–Weil group.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] The case with A an elliptic curve E and K the field of rational numbers is **Mordell's theorem**, answering a question apparently posed by Henri Poincaré around 1901; it was proven by Louis Mordell in 1922.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] It is a foundational theorem of Diophantine geometry and the arithmetic of abelian varieties.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] The *tangent-chord process* (one form of addition theorem on a cubic curve) had been known as far back as the seventeenth century.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] The process of infinite descent of Fermat was well known, but Mordell succeeded in establishing the finiteness of the quotient group $E(\mathbb {Q} )/2E(\mathbb {Q} )$ which forms a major step in the proof.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] Certainly the finiteness of this group is a necessary condition for $E(\mathbb {Q} )$ to be finitely generated; and it shows that the rank is finite.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] This turns out to be the essential difficulty.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] It can be proved by direct analysis of the doubling of a point on *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] Some years later André Weil took up the subject, producing the generalisation to Jacobians of higher genus curves over arbitrary number fields in his doctoral dissertation published in 1928.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] More abstract methods were required, to carry out a proof with the same basic structure.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] The second half of the proof needs some type of height function, in terms of which to bound the 'size' of points of $A(K)$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] Some measure of the co-ordinates will do; heights are logarithmic, so that (roughly speaking) it is a question of how many digits are required to write down a set of homogeneous coordinates.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] For an abelian variety, there is no *a priori* preferred representation, though, as a projective variety.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/mordell-weil-theorem] Both halves of the proof have been improved significantly by subsequent technical advances: in Galois cohomology as applied to descent, and in the study of the best height functions (which are quadratic forms).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In mathematics, the **rank of an elliptic curve** is the rational Mordell–Weil rank of an elliptic curve E defined over the field of rational numbers or more generally a number field *K*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Mordell's theorem (generalized to arbitrary number fields by André Weil) says the group of rational points on an elliptic curve has a finite basis.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This means that for any elliptic curve there is a finite subset of the rational points on the curve, from which all further rational points may be generated.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] If the number of rational points on a curve is infinite then some point in a finite basis must have infinite order.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] The number of *independent* basis points with infinite order is the rank of the curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] where $E(K)_{\text{tors}}$ is the torsion group of *E*, for which comparatively much is known, and $r\in \mathbb {Z} _{\geq 0}$ is a nonnegative integer called the **rank of E (over *K*)**.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] The rank is related to several outstanding problems in number theory, most notably the Birch–Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] There is currently no consensus among the experts on whether one should expect the ranks of elliptic curves over $\mathbb {Q}$ to be bounded or not.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] It has been shown that there exist curves with rank at least 29, but it is widely believed that such curves are rare.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Indeed, Goldfeld and later Katz–Sarnak conjectured that in a suitable asymptotic sense (see below), the rank of elliptic curves should be 1/2 on average.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] An even stronger conjecture is that half of all elliptic curves should have rank 0 (meaning that the infinite part of its Mordell–Weil group is trivial) and the other half should have rank 1; all remaining ranks consist of a total of 0% of all elliptic curves over $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In order to obtain a reasonable notion of 'average', one must be able to count elliptic curves $E/\mathbb {Q}$ somehow.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This requires the introduction of a height function on the set of rational elliptic curves.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Moreover, this model is unique if for any prime number p such that $p^{4}$ divides A , we have $p^{6}\nmid B$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] It can then be shown that the number of elliptic curves $E/\mathbb {Q}$ with bounded height $H(E)$ is finite.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] We denote by $r(E)$ the Mordell–Weil rank of the elliptic curve $E/\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] It is not known whether or not this limit exists.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] However, by replacing the limit with the limit superior, one can obtain a well-defined quantity.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Obtaining estimates for this quantity is therefore obtaining upper bounds for the size of the average rank of elliptic curves (provided that an average exists).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In the past two decades there has been some progress made towards the task of finding upper bounds for the average rank.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Brumer showed that, conditioned on the Birch–Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture and the Generalized Riemann hypothesis that one can obtain an upper bound of $2.3$ for the average rank.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Heath-Brown showed that one can obtain an upper bound of 2 , still assuming the same two conjectures.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Finally, Young showed that one can obtain a bound of $25/14$ , still assuming both conjectures.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Bhargava and Shankar showed that the average rank of elliptic curves is bounded above by $1.5$ and ${\frac {7}{6}}$ without assuming either the Birch–Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture or the Generalized Riemann Hypothesis.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This is achieved by computing the average size of the 2 -Selmer and 3 -Selmer groups of elliptic curves $E/\mathbb {Q}$ respectively.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Bhargava and Shankar's unconditional proof of the boundedness of the average rank of elliptic curves is obtained by using a certain exact sequence involving the Mordell-Weil group of an elliptic curve $E/\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Denote by $E(\mathbb {Q} )$ the Mordell-Weil group of rational points on the elliptic curve E , $\operatorname {Sel} _{p}(E)$ the p -Selmer group of E , and let Ш ${}_{E}[p]$ denote the p -part of the Tate–Shafarevich group of E .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This shows that the *rank* of $\operatorname {Sel} _{p}(E)$ , also called the p -Selmer rank of E , defined as the non-negative integer s such that $\#\operatorname {Sel} _{p}(E)=p^{s}$ , is an upper bound for the Mordell-Weil rank r of $E(\mathbb {Q} )$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Therefore, if one can compute or obtain an upper bound on p -Selmer rank of E , then one would be able to bound the Mordell-Weil rank on average as well.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In *Binary quartic forms having bounded invariants, and the boundedness of the average rank of elliptic curves*, Bhargava and Shankar computed the 2-Selmer rank of elliptic curves on average.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] They did so by counting *binary quartic forms*, using a method used by Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer in their original computation of the analytic rank of elliptic curves which led to their famous conjecture.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] It is in general an open problem whether the rank of all elliptic curves over a fixed field *K* is bounded by a number ${\tilde {B}}_{K}$ or not.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This problem has a long history of opinions of experts in the field about it.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] A popular article can be found in Quanta magazine.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] For technical reasons instead of ${\tilde {B}}_{K}$ one considers $B_{K}$ the (potentially infinite) bound on ${\text{rk}}(E(K))$ of elliptic curves *E* defined over *K* that occurs for infinitely many different such *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Néron in 1950 held the existence of an absolute bound $B_{\mathbb {Q} }$ for the rank $r_{E}$ probable.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In 1966 Cassels, 1974 Tate and 1982 Mestre expressed their disbelief in such a bound $B_{K}$ in various generality regarding *K*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This was the consensus among the leading experts up to the 2010s.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] However Mestre in 1982 proved unconditionally that for elliptic curves *E* over $\mathbb {Q}$ there is a bound ${\text{rk}}(E(\mathbb {Q} ))\leq O(\log(N(E)))$ in terms of the conductor of an elliptic curve $N(E)$ which itself is unbounded for varying *E*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In 2016 Park et al. introduced a new random model drawing on analogies to the Cohen-Lenstra heuristics for class groups of number fields and the Keating-Snaith heuristics based on random matrix theory for L-functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Their model was geared along the known results on distribution of elliptic curves in low ranks and their Tate-Shafarevich groups.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] The model makes further predictions on upper bounds which are consistent with all currently known lower bounds from example families of elliptic curves in special cases (such as restrictions on the type of torsion groups).
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] For *K* a general number field the same model would predict the same bound, which however cannot hold.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] They attribute the failure of their model in this case to the existence of elliptic curves *E* over general number fields *K* which come from base change of a proper subfield $K_{0}\subsetneq K$ , which their model does not take into account.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Instead of the family ${\mathcal {E}}_{K}$ of all elliptic curves defined over *K* they suggest to consider only the family ${\mathcal {E}}_{K}^{\circ }\subset {\mathcal {E}}_{K}$ of all such elliptic curves that do not come from base change of a proper subfield.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] As of 2024 there is no consensus among the experts if the rank of an elliptic curve should be expected to be bounded uniformly only in terms of its base number field or not.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Park et al. argue that their model (suitably modified) should not only apply to number fields, but to general global fields, in particular including when *K* is a function field over a finite field.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] They also point out that function fields *K* are known to exist with $B_{K}=\infty$ , but that $B_{K}^{\circ }<\infty$ for all such *K* cannot be ruled out.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] For the question of boundedness of ranks of elliptic curves over some field *K* to make sense, one needs a Mordell-Weil-type theorem over that field that guarantees finite generation for the group *K*-rational points.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This holds much more generally than only for global fields, by a result of Néron this is true for all *K* finitely generated over their prime field.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] This fails for local fields such as $K\in \{\mathbb {R} ,\mathbb {C} ,\mathbb {Q} _{p},\mathbb {F} _{q}((x))\}$ , as the group of rational points is no longer finitely generated.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In this case the rank will always be infinite.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] But for general *K* there is no universal analog in place of the rank that is an interesting object of study.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] A common conjecture is that there is no bound on the largest possible rank for an elliptic curve over $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In 2006, Noam Elkies discovered an elliptic curve with a rank of at least 28.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] Many other examples of (families of) elliptic curves over $\mathbb {Q}$ are known.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/rank-of-an-elliptic-curve] In particular Elkies gave an infinite family of elliptic curves over $\mathbb {Q}$ each of rank at least 19.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In mathematics, the **Weierstrass elliptic functions** are elliptic functions that take a particularly simple form.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This class of functions is also referred to as **℘-functions** and they are usually denoted by the symbol ℘, a uniquely fancy script *p*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] They play an important role in the theory of elliptic functions, i.e., meromorphic functions that are doubly periodic.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] A ℘-function together with its derivative can be used to parameterize elliptic curves and they generate the field of elliptic functions with respect to a given period lattice.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Yet one still wants to find a way to parameterize it.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In a similar way one can get a parameterization of $C_{g_{2},g_{3}}^{\mathbb {C} }$ by means of the doubly periodic $\wp$ -function and its derivative, namely via $(x,y)=(\wp (z),\wp '(z))$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This parameterization has the domain $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ , which is topologically equivalent to a torus.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] There is another analogy to the trigonometric functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] So the sine function is an inverse function of an integral function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Elliptic functions are the inverse functions of elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This invertibility is used in complex analysis to provide a solution to certain nonlinear differential equations satisfying the Painlevé property, i.e., those equations that admit poles as their only movable singularities.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Let $\omega _{1},\omega _{2}\in \mathbb {C}$ be two complex numbers that are linearly independent over $\mathbb {R}$ and let ${\displaystyle \Lambda$ be the period lattice generated by those numbers.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This series converges locally uniformly absolutely in the complex torus $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It is common to use 1 and $\tau$ in the upper half-plane $\mathbb {H$ as generators of the lattice.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Dividing by ${\textstyle \omega _{1}}$ maps the lattice $\mathbb {Z} \omega _{1}+\mathbb {Z} \omega _{2}$ isomorphically onto the lattice $\mathbb {Z} +\mathbb {Z} \tau$ with ${\textstyle \tau ={\tfrac {\omega _{2}}{\omega _{1}}}}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Because $-\tau$ can be substituted for $\tau$ , without loss of generality we can assume $\tau \in \mathbb {H}$ , and then define $\wp (z,\tau ):=\wp (z,1,\tau )$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Since the sum converges absolutely this rearrangement does not change the limit.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Then the $\wp$ -function satisfies the differential equation $\wp '^{2}(z)=4\wp ^{3}(z)-g_{2}\wp (z)-g_{3}.$ This relation can be verified by forming a linear combination of powers of $\wp$ and $\wp '$ to eliminate the pole at $z=0$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This yields an entire elliptic function that has to be constant by Liouville's theorem.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The coefficients of the above differential equation $g_{2}$ and $g_{3}$ are known as the *invariants*.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Because they depend on the lattice $\Lambda$ they can be viewed as functions in $\omega _{1}$ and $\omega _{2}$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The series expansion suggests that $g_{2}$ and $g_{3}$ are homogeneous functions of degree $-4$ and $-6$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] If $\omega _{1}$ and $\omega _{2}$ are chosen in such a way that $\operatorname {Im} \left({\tfrac {\omega _{2}}{\omega _{1}}}\right)>0$ , $g_{2}$ and $g_{3}$ can be interpreted as functions on the upper half-plane $\mathbb {H$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The *modular discriminant* $\Delta$ is defined as the discriminant of the characteristic polynomial of the differential equation $\wp '^{2}(z)=4\wp ^{3}(z)-g_{2}\wp (z)-g_{3}$ as follows: $\Delta =g_{2}^{3}-27g_{3}^{2}.$ The discriminant is a modular form of weight $12$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] That is, under the action of the modular group, it transforms as $\Delta \left({\frac {a\tau +b}{c\tau +d}}\right)=\left(c\tau +d\right)^{12}\Delta (\tau )$ where $a,b,d,c\in \mathbb {Z}$ with $ad-bc=1$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Note that $\Delta =(2\pi )^{12}\eta ^{24}$ where $\eta$ is the Dedekind eta function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] For the Fourier coefficients of $\Delta$ , see Ramanujan tau function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] $e_{1}$ , $e_{2}$ and $e_{3}$ are the roots of the cubic polynomial $4\wp (z)^{3}-g_{2}\wp (z)-g_{3}$ and are related by the equation: $e_{1}+e_{2}+e_{3}=0.$ Because those roots are distinct the discriminant $\Delta$ does not vanish on the upper half plane.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] For numerical work, it is often convenient to calculate the Weierstrass elliptic function in terms of Jacobi's elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This also provides a very rapid algorithm for computing $\wp (z,\tau )$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] where O is a point lying on the line at infinity $\mathbb {P} _{1}(\mathbb {C} )$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] For this cubic there exists no rational parameterization, if $\Delta \neq 0$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In this case it is also called an elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Now the map $\varphi$ is bijective and parameterizes the elliptic curve ${\bar {C}}_{g_{2},g_{3}}^{\mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ is an abelian group and a topological space, equipped with the quotient topology.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It can be shown that every Weierstrass cubic is given in such a way.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The statement that elliptic curves over $\mathbb {Q}$ can be parameterized over $\mathbb {Q}$ , is known as the modularity theorem.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This is an important theorem in number theory.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It was part of Andrew Wiles' proof (1995) of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This can be proven by considering constants $A,B$ such that $\wp '(z)=A\wp (z)+B,\quad \wp '(w)=A\wp (w)+B.$ Then the elliptic function $\wp '(\zeta )-A\wp (\zeta )-B$ has a pole of order three at zero, and therefore three zeros whose sum belongs to $\Lambda$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Two of the zeros are z and w , and thus the third is congruent to $-z-w$ .
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This can be proven from the addition theorem shown above.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Any elliptic function f can be expressed as: $f(u)=c\prod _{i=1}^{n}{\frac {\sigma (u-a_{i})}{\sigma (u-b_{i})}}\quad c\in \mathbb {C}$ where $\sigma$ is the Weierstrass sigma function and $a_{i},b_{i}$ are the respective zeros and poles in the period parallelogram.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The Weierstrass's elliptic function is usually written with a rather special, lower case script letter ℘, which was Weierstrass's own notation introduced in his lectures of 1862–1863.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It should not be confused with the normal mathematical script letters P: 𝒫 and 𝓅.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In computing, the letter ℘ is available as `\wp` in TeX.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In Unicode the code point is U+2118 ℘ SCRIPT CAPITAL P, with the more correct alias weierstrass elliptic function.
[src:elliptic-curves-math/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In HTML, it can be escaped as `&weierp;` or `&wp;`.
